We attended the, "Odyssey of the Mind" event last Saturday. I had charged my Tesla up to 90% at the Double Tree hotel but needed a full range charge to comfortably get back to Buffalo. I had contacted Ms. Susan Crane, the Parking Services Director via email (scrane@binghamton.edu) about a week prior to the event and asked for access to the chargers in the ramp D parking garage. I was given an access code to input into the keypad of a specific charger. At the gate to the ramp the attendant had received a copy of the info needed to get me access and I connected without a problem. Later that evening, we returned home with 24 miles on the battery. Paid the $6 event parking fee. Charger was otherwise free. 30A@208V. Very shortly the issue will be less compelling since the Syracuse Supercharger should be online in a week.

The valet who showed me the stations said they had been there since the hotel opened about a year ago.  I had pestered this hotel about putting in EVSEs during construction last year but never heard anything back.  The valet said he'd seen several cars use it.

To those whom use these stations, please help us, the ev community. Only charge for as long as you need to to get home, and plug in at home as well, don't abuse the chargers, others need them as well. Also, please leave a note on your vehicle, or on PlugShare, about if and when it would be acceptable to unplug your vehicle if you are not around and/or contact information to inquire. If your car is equipped with an unplug alarm, and you can't be contacted, please disable the alarm. To the Tesla specifically, I've notice you parked and plugged in day after day for hours and hours. Unless you have a VERY long drive to campus, I would have to assume you're abusing the system by not plugging in at home. Either way, please help the community in one of a few ways. A Tesla supercharger is located a few miles away, please use that if you need a lot of power. Also, your car has a ChaDeMo option, please invest in that option and use the fast charger. Many cars don't have a fast charge option, so a lengthy use of that would, in most cases, be ideal. Also, when your car is done charging, please move your car as soon as possible. To anyone who lives on campus, please refrain from using the chargers during the day which is when commuters may need them, a overnight charge is almost always perfectly fine.

I think a lot of Leaf drivers don't realize that quick charging above 80% isn't quick charging. Below about 60% you charge at about 120amps it begins tapering. The charger drops the supplied amps very sharply. You probably charge just as fast on Level2 above around 90%. I waited while a guy charged well above 95%. It was charging at a paltry 9 amps. I flagged the guy and said "you're charging at 9 amps, it will take like 15 minutes to finish that last couple percent" he seemed angry and said "You're kicking me out? Just take the charger." I feel like a jerk but he was wasting both of our time. Just thought I'd give a PSA.

Connecticut DOT & Tesla Motors are jointly updating charging signage at the 2 Greenwich Service Plazas on the Merritt Pkwy (CT-15).  Due to high parking stall utilization at these plazas, posted stalls shall be used for SHARED parking or EV charging:

Joel,  If you haven't been watching the EV Fast Charger prices, I can understand your reaction to our price.  Here is a sample of our Fast Charging competition.  The Blink network charges $0.65/kWh ($0.59 for members) and eVgo, charges $4.95 + $0.20/minute or >$10 for a 30 minute charge.  The average fast charge at our site is about 10 kWh, which would be $8.90 for a charge of about 30 minutes.  Both Blink and eVgo networks were built on government grants with equipment not meant for a coastal environment.  

As for usage, we did not see a dramatic increase in usage when technical problems caused us to offer fast charging for free this summer and we have not seen a dramatic decrease in usage now that we have resumed charging for the power.

We are constrained by our costs.  Commercial power costs $0.24/kWh and we risk a $3.00/kWh demand charge if the fast charger causes us to exceed peak demand.  We also have network, insurance, security, rent and the installation costs.  The fast charger costs 6-7 times what the 220v charger costs, which means a higher price to use.
  
So, we're not going to offer fast charging at the same price as 220v charging, instead we offer drivers a choice.  You can balance the extra hour charging time versus the extra $5.00 for 10kWh.  The important thing is that an area of California that was not conveniently accessible to EVs now is.  We have customers using both chargers and we welcome everyone.

Sincerely,
Richard Sachen
Sunspeed Enterprises

Relaying another checkin from a friend ... With his Model S cord and the NEMA 14-50 receptacle, he found that his charging cable got quite hot.  Typically this is because of a bad wiring connection somewhere, and could be in the receptacle not the cord (with the excess heat then flowing from the receptacle to the cord through the wiring metal).  For that reason some Tesla Model S owners have been backing off the current draw, say down to 25 Amps.  He did that, overnight, and got a full charge.

This is my first time at a ChargePoint station. I just got the car--in fact it's my first charge. 

Smarter EV owners would know to learn about chargepoint prior to driving to one with only 9 miles of charge left. 

I parked, the unit was locked--meaning it needed the card to activate it. I don't have a card, so I went in the the Marriott to ask for one. 

They couldn't find it. After about 5 minutes I gave up and decided to crawl over to Amerigreen or the Hampton. 

But on a whim I called Chargepoint and learned they can unlock it from afar over the interwebs. This internet thing is going to be big. 

You can also unlock it from their app, but there's no mention of that at the app store. Important safety tip, Egon. 

They got me going and it's charging now. 

The Marriott staff were very friendly and accommodating--they just didn't know (like me) how it worked. I impressed upon them the importance of the staff knowing, and having a card handy. 

It worked out nicely--I'm sitting in their lobby cafe, about to work for an hour over coffee and eggs. Not farm fresh, free-range organic eggs, but it's a meal. :)

Fiat was wrong to unplug the Volt. Volt is same concept as BMW i3 Rexx, a range extended electric vehicle (EREV) . Volt has 44 miles range usually  ( 55-60 in new model) with an electric generator powered by gasoline engine which is active when the battery is considered depleted. A driver can fully accelerate a volt to top speed and the gasoline generator will not turn on as long as battery is not empty. A plug-in hybrid would require help from a gasoline powered engine to accelerate under those conditions and many less demanding conditions.

Nissan NCTC

2015-05-10
Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps under their current design should have separate listings for L3s so that status (like under repair) and alerts (like all stations in use and station has become available) make sense for real human EV users.    
                                                 Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are failing to be honest in several ways:

0. Many stations are out of order, but not listed as such on the advertising posters in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for under repair. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of order but still using the normally working icon.

1. They do not provide 30-minute free sessions.

2. They fail to time the sessions for you.

3. They fail to cut off the session at 30 minutes.

4. If you go over, they charge you $7. This requires you to leave work or whatever you are doing, exactly in time to cut it off. If you leave too early, then you cut your session short. If you leave right on time, you must still cut your session a little short to avoid going over the 30 minutes on your own timing.

5. They refuse to document or provide measures for when the timer starts and when it ends.

6. When touch screens do not work, you cannot use NCTC over app or telephone. They say you can dispute it later, but their dispute process is opaque and time consuming. That is not a free 30-minute charge, either.

7. What they should have done, and what they probably originally meant to do, is simply provide $7 fast charges for free to NCTC customers.

Fiat was wrong to unplug the Volt. Volt is same concept as BMW i3 Rexx, a range extended electric vehicle (EREV) . Volt has 44 miles range usually  ( 55-60 in new model) with an electric generator powered by gasoline engine which is active when the battery is considered depleted. A driver can fully accelerate a volt to top speed and the gasoline generator will not turn on as long as battery is not empty. A plug-in hybrid would require help from a gasoline powered engine to accelerate under those conditions and many less demanding conditions.

Hi folks. We charged there on Saturday, October 5, and although the charging itself was successful, they booted our Nissan. There were no signs or warnings about the time limit that you can charge your car, or about the possibility of booting. So we filed a complaint with the Department of Consumer Affairs of NYC regarding they unlawful booting, in the absence of signs. Also, from DCA I found out that only towing companies are authorized to boot, the removal of the boot should be up to $25, paid in cash or credit, and the boot should be removed within 30 minutes from the time you paid the fine. They charged us $75 and demanded cash only. We are disputing this issue now and we'll let you know how it is going. Either way, it is illegal to be booted unless there are very obvious signs about that and the booting is done by a licensed company: http://www.nyc.gov/html/dca/downloads/pdf/booting_law_rules.pdf

Have an expired evGo card but had to call toll-free number. Support person helpful, was able to start charging ASAP. However, the price for a one-time charge is significantly higher than other providers. $9.95 for 30 minutes which took me to 10 bars from 3 bars. Other providers such as Blink and Charge Point charge less or offer a better subscription plan for lower rates. Blink membership is free or low cost and offers $1 per hour L2 charging and $2 per hour non-member. L3 charging for members is approximately $5-8, depending on location, for members. Charge Point is comparably priced, depending on location. While it was handy having this DCQC, I'll avoid it in the future if possible as a poor value for approximately $3 worth of electricity with a $6.95 "convenience charge" for QC. I don't like their subscription model as it's more expensive than others...

TESLA OWNERS - MODEL S UPGRADE - They have a brand new cable, Model S adapter and the Tesla approved socket to plug it into. With 40 amps, charged my P85D at 25 mi/hr. He got out the brand new Tesla cable and adapter and then, with his cell phone light, got it plugged into the Castle & connected the car. Full charge this morning!  Plus charger is at back of one of the two handicap spaces right next to the front door.  You have to be a guest but there's really nowhere else to go once you drive up the long drive to the top of the hill. GREAT destination connection though, as dinner guests at Equus often linger up to 4 hours so that's 100 extra miles if you need it (or just top off) or a full charge every night if you're staying here.  The staff is helpful and knowledgable - really top notch. Come on MODEL S OWNERS lets lobby to get a couple of the 100amp home chargers in here like the places along the west coast that have MADE themselves destinations for Model S owners, convenient and comfortable for the only long distance, fast and fun, total EV made (just drove from OR to San Fransisco, to here, NYC, 4500 miles + in new P85D in less then two weeks - home to north of Boston tomorrow).  Thank you PlugShare members who added crucial extra info to charging locations - I couldn't have made it without you. Fiat was wrong to unplug the Volt. Volt is same concept as BMW i3 Rexx, a range extended electric vehicle (EREV) . Volt has 44 miles range usually  ( 55-60 in new model) with an electric generator powered by gasoline engine which is active when the battery is considered depleted. A driver can fully accelerate a volt to top speed and the gasoline generator will not turn on as long as battery is not empty. A plug-in hybrid would require help from a gasoline powered engine to accelerate under those conditions and many less demanding conditions.

On the 28th, I successfully charged using the working (left) charger for almost a half hour.  On the 29th, the same one stopped after 10 minutes.  I called Blink to explain and they were able to start the right side remotely (as a one-time "favor") to allow me to finish my charge.  (The broken screen only prevents drivers from using it!)

The rep said it was a one-time only favor and that essentially I should wait until they were fixed before relying on them again.  When I asked how I'd know without going there, he had no advice.  Great.  I hope it is soon (and that they develop a notification system as eVgo appears to have).

So until then, you're taking a risk coming here: the left side might stop prematurely, and you will only get one "grace" charge from the right side.

An absolutely fabulous experience parking on Cannery Row in Monterey at the Clement hotel's new Chargepoint chargers. The entrance is on Wave Street, 1 block behind the Clement Intercontinental. The EVSE is free with the Chargepoint RFID card. The typical Level 2 J1772 and Level 1 door lock that will clear when authorized. When I pulled up to the ticket gate, the cashier immediately said "Up one level and to the right" It was so refreshing to have someone immediately point out where the charger was. There are two chargers in the corner with well marked spaces for EVs. The cords are clean, nice and long so you can head in if you like. Flat rate parking is $8. You can then walk out to the recreation trail or back out to wave street, however when you return, return to the pedestrian entrance on Wave street. You can use the cashier on the main floor or pay on exit with your credit card. EVSEs are not reserve-able, but you can check status on the Chargepoint website/app before you arrive.
